{"parse":{"title":"Catafalque","pageid":712306,"revid":849137137,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:252px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Krzysztof_Opalinski_dead_Sierakow.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/Krzysztof_Opalinski_dead_Sierakow.jpg/250px-Krzysztof_Opalinski_dead_Sierakow.jpg\" width=\"250\" height=\"162\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/Krzysztof_Opalinski_dead_Sierakow.jpg/375px-Krzysztof_Opalinski_dead_Sierakow.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/Krzysztof_Opalinski_dead_Sierakow.jpg/500px-Krzysztof_Opalinski_dead_Sierakow.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1200\" data-file-height=\"776\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Krzysztof_Opalinski_dead_Sierakow.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Catafalque of <a href=\"/wiki/Krzysztof_Opali%C5%84ski\" title=\"Krzysztof Opali\u0144ski\">Krzysztof Opali\u0144ski</a>, 17th century</div></div></div>\n<p>A <b>catafalque</b> is a raised <a href=\"/wiki/Bier\" title=\"Bier\">bier</a>, box, or similar platform, often movable, that is used to support the <a href=\"/wiki/Casket\" title=\"Casket\">casket</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Coffin\" title=\"Coffin\">coffin</a>, or body of the deceased during a <a href=\"/wiki/Christian_burial\" title=\"Christian burial\">Christian funeral</a> or memorial service.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Jobson2009_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Jobson2009-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Following a <a href=\"/wiki/Roman_Catholic\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Roman Catholic\">Roman Catholic</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Requiem_Mass\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Requiem Mass\">Requiem Mass</a>, a catafalque may be used to stand in place of the body at the <a href=\"/wiki/Absolution_of_the_dead\" title=\"Absolution of the dead\">absolution of the dead</a> or used during Masses of the Dead and <a href=\"/wiki/All_Souls%27_Day\" title=\"All Souls&#39; Day\">All Souls' Day</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-EmpereurFern\u00e1ndez2006_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-EmpereurFern\u00e1ndez2006-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>According to Peter Stanford, the term originates from the <a href=\"/wiki/Italian_language\" title=\"Italian language\">Italian</a> <i><i><span lang=\"it\" title=\"Italian language text\">catafalco</span></i></i>, which means <a href=\"/wiki/Scaffolding\" title=\"Scaffolding\">scaffolding</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Stanford2013_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Stanford2013-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> However, the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Oxford_English_Dictionary\" title=\"Oxford English Dictionary\">Oxford English Dictionary</a></i> says the word is \"[o]f unknown derivation; even the original form is uncertain; French pointing to <i><span lang=\"fr\" title=\"French language text\">-fald-</span></i> or <i><span lang=\"fr\" title=\"French language text\">-falt-</span></i>, Italian to <i><span lang=\"it\" title=\"Italian language text\">-falc-</span></i>, Spanish to <i><span lang=\"es\" title=\"Spanish language text\">-fals</span></i>.\" The most notable Italian catafalque was the one designed for <a href=\"/wiki/Michelangelo\" title=\"Michelangelo\">Michelangelo</a> by his fellow artists in 1564.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Cornelison2012_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Cornelison2012-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> An elaborate and highly decorated roofed surround for a catafalque,<sup id=\"cite_ref-Bull1998_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Bull1998-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> common for grand funerals of the <a href=\"/wiki/Baroque\" title=\"Baroque\">Baroque</a> era, may be called a <i><i><span lang=\"la\" title=\"Latin language text\"><a href=\"/wiki/Castrum_doloris\" title=\"Castrum doloris\">castrum doloris</a></span></i></i>.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Papal_catafalques\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Papal catafalques</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Notable_catafalques\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Notable catafalques</span></a>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Voltaire\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2.1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Voltaire</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Abraham_Lincoln\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2.2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Abraham Lincoln</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#Notes\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Notes</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-7\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Papal_catafalques\">Papal catafalques</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Catafalque&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Papal catafalques\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Large processions have followed the catafalques of <a href=\"/wiki/List_of_popes\" title=\"List of popes\">Popes</a>. The households of the cardinals carried the catafalque of <a href=\"/wiki/Pope_Sixtus_V\" title=\"Pope Sixtus V\">Pope Sixtus V</a> in 1590. The bier, decorated with gold cloth, was followed by \"confraternities, <a href=\"/wiki/Religious_order\" title=\"Religious order\">religious orders</a>, students of seminaries and colleges, orphans and <a href=\"/wiki/Mendicant\" title=\"Mendicant\">mendicants</a>\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> In 1963, a million people filed past the catafalque of <a href=\"/wiki/Pope_John_XXIII\" title=\"Pope John XXIII\">Pope John XXIII</a>, which had been carried in procession to <a href=\"/wiki/St._Peter%27s_Basilica\" title=\"St. Peter&#39;s Basilica\">St. Peter's Basilica</a> in Rome.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notable_catafalques\">Notable catafalques</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Catafalque&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Notable catafalques\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Voltaire_cercueil_fun%C3%A9railles_Panth%C3%A9on.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d3/Voltaire_cercueil_fun%C3%A9railles_Panth%C3%A9on.jpg/220px-Voltaire_cercueil_fun%C3%A9railles_Panth%C3%A9on.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"245\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d3/Voltaire_cercueil_fun%C3%A9railles_Panth%C3%A9on.jpg/330px-Voltaire_cercueil_fun%C3%A9railles_Panth%C3%A9on.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d3/Voltaire_cercueil_fun%C3%A9railles_Panth%C3%A9on.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"434\" data-file-height=\"484\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Voltaire_cercueil_fun%C3%A9railles_Panth%C3%A9on.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div><a href=\"/wiki/Voltaire\" title=\"Voltaire\">Voltaire</a>'s catafalque</div></div></div>\n<p>Other than religious leaders such as Popes, famous people have lain in state or been carried in procession to their burial place on a catafalque.\n</p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Voltaire\">Voltaire</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Catafalque&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Voltaire\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>Thirteen years after his death, the remains of <a href=\"/wiki/Voltaire\" title=\"Voltaire\">Voltaire</a> were transferred on a catafalque to the <a href=\"/wiki/Panth%C3%A9on\" title=\"Panth\u00e9on\">Panth\u00e9on</a> in Paris, a building dedicated to the great men of the French nation. It bore the inscription: \"Poet, philosopher, historian, he made a great step forward in the human spirit. He prepared us to become free.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Abraham_Lincoln\">Abraham Lincoln</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Catafalque&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Abraham Lincoln\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<div class=\"thumb tleft\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:LincolnCatafalque.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/24/LincolnCatafalque.jpg/220px-LincolnCatafalque.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"165\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/24/LincolnCatafalque.jpg/330px-LincolnCatafalque.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/24/LincolnCatafalque.jpg/440px-LincolnCatafalque.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"845\" data-file-height=\"634\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:LincolnCatafalque.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>The <a href=\"/wiki/Lincoln_catafalque\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Lincoln catafalque\">Lincoln catafalque</a> in the <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_Capitol\" title=\"United States Capitol\">United States Capitol</a></div></div></div>\n<p>The <a href=\"/wiki/Lincoln_catafalque\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Lincoln catafalque\">Lincoln catafalque</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-Coggeshall1865_9-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Coggeshall1865-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> first used for United States President <a href=\"/wiki/Abraham_Lincoln\" title=\"Abraham Lincoln\">Abraham Lincoln</a>'s funeral in 1865, has been used for all those who have <a href=\"/wiki/Lying_in_state\" title=\"Lying in state\">lain in state</a> in the <a href=\"/wiki/Capitol_Rotunda\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Capitol Rotunda\">Capitol Rotunda</a> since Lincoln's death. When not in use, the catafalque is kept on display in the Exhibition Hall at the <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_Capitol_Visitor_Center\" title=\"United States Capitol Visitor Center\">United States Capitol Visitor Center</a>. It was used for <a href=\"/wiki/Antonin_Scalia\" title=\"Antonin Scalia\">Antonin Scalia</a>, an <a href=\"/wiki/Associate_Justice_of_the_Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States\" title=\"Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States\">Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States</a>, in 2016. Commentators noted that the structure of the original pine timbers and boards has been reinforced, albeit being left 'original'.<sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div style=\"clear:both;\"></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Catafalque&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Limbers_and_caissons\" title=\"Limbers and caissons\">Caisson</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Catafalque_party\" title=\"Catafalque party\">Catafalque party</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes\">Notes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Catafalque&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6\" title=\"Edit section: Notes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Jobson2009-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Jobson2009_1-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Christopher Jobson (2009). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=5wZa2sr3ol8C&amp;pg=PA71\"><i>Looking Forward Looking Back: Customs and Traditions of the Australian Army</i></a>. Big Sky Publishing. pp.&#160;71\u2013. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-9803251-6-4\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-0-9803251-6-4\">978-0-9803251-6-4</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Looking+Forward+Looking+Back%3A+Customs+and+Traditions+of+the+Australian+Army&amp;rft.pages=71-&amp;rft.pub=Big+Sky+Publishing&amp;rft.date=2009&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-9803251-6-4&amp;rft.au=Christopher+Jobson&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D5wZa2sr3ol8C%26pg%3DPA71&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACatafalque\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-EmpereurFern\u00e1ndez2006-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-EmpereurFern\u00e1ndez2006_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">James Empereur; Eduardo Fern\u00e1ndez (12 October 2006). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=GQVvAAAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PA294\"><i>La Vida Sacra: Contemporary Hispanic Sacramental Theology</i></a>. Rowman &amp; Littlefield Publishers. pp.&#160;294\u2013. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-1-4616-3855-1\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-1-4616-3855-1\">978-1-4616-3855-1</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=La+Vida+Sacra%3A+Contemporary+Hispanic+Sacramental+Theology&amp;rft.pages=294-&amp;rft.pub=Rowman+%26+Littlefield+Publishers&amp;rft.date=2006-10-12&amp;rft.isbn=978-1-4616-3855-1&amp;rft.au=James+Empereur&amp;rft.au=Eduardo+Fern%C3%A1ndez&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DGQVvAAAAQBAJ%26pg%3DPA294&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACatafalque\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Stanford2013-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Stanford2013_3-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Peter Stanford (23 May 2013). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=AYVMAQAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PA244\"><i>How to Read a Graveyard: Journeys in the Company of the Dead</i></a>. A&amp;C Black. pp.&#160;244\u2013. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-1-4411-7977-7\" title=\"Special:BookSour